external_knowledge:
Active industries, locations, and companies refer to those with an 'is_active' status of 1;
The average pay range is calculated using the midpoint of the salary range (average salary = (min salary + max salary) / 2).;
Employment types may include full-time, part-time, and internship positions.

- "hidden treasure troves of opportunity" refers to job postings;
- "bustling heart of Manhattan" refers to locations related to New York;
- "golden gates of employment" refers to employment opportunities;
- "lighthouses" corresponds to companies;
- "harbors" corresponds to locations;
- "navigational charts" corresponds to detailed descriptions of jobs;
- "beckoning opportunities" refers to job titles and details;
- "weary sailor" refers to the job seeker.

- 'Flurry of activity' refers to a high number of applications;
- 'Lower-paying' refers to job postings with a maximum salary below $100,000;
- 'Tech positions' include roles such as software engineers, data scientists, and machine learning engineers;
- 'Within the last month' means applications made since the last 30 days from the current date.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT job_category)
FROM job_postings
WHERE industry_id = 1 AND salary_min > 100000;

SELECT i.industry_name, ias.average_salary
FROM industries AS i
JOIN industry_average_salaries AS ias ON i.industry_id = ias.industry_id;

SELECT job_postings.title, companies.company_name
FROM job_postings
JOIN companies ON job_postings.company_id = companies.company_id;

SELECT COUNT(*) AS total_applications
FROM job_applications
WHERE seeker_id = (SELECT seeker_id FROM job_seekers WHERE name = 'John Doe');
